<p>What kind of world would it be if people gave themselves to what they&rsquo;re doing the way children give themselves to play?</p>
</blockquote>

<p>I told these things to my therapist, speaking from a cavernous pit of guilt from which I thought I would never emerge. He listened until I finished, and said, &ldquo;You&rsquo;ve put a mask on that person from the past. You&rsquo;re seeing him as evil and wicked. I want you to look back, and take that mask off him, and see him as he really was.&rdquo; As I looked back, the mask he was wearing seemed one of pain not of evil, and as I lifted it off I saw a man &mdash; and a boy &mdash; who only wanted to be loved and accepted, who had twisted himself into various contortions because he didn&rsquo;t believe he deserved love, who had looked for love and acceptance in the wrong ways and in the wrong places and had often found something that wasn&rsquo;t love at all, that didn&rsquo;t begin to touch his hunger. But he wasn&rsquo;t wicked. He didn&rsquo;t deserve blame, but I had been blaming him. I had been speaking with the voice of conventional society &mdash; the world I had been brought up in &mdash; and I had been blaming him for everything that seemed to have gone wrong in his life. I had been beating the shit out of him.</p>

<p>What I actually saw at that moment in the therapist&rsquo;s office &mdash; and if my mouth wasn&rsquo;t agape literally it certainly was figuratively &mdash; was so vast that it took weeks to sort out. I saw that the guilt I was feeling, and my existence as a guilt-feeling person, went way back, before any memory, certainly before that six-year-old put himself over his friend&rsquo;s knee to be spanked. I saw that my guilt didn&rsquo;t really have to do with the failures of my marriage, or with anything I was feeling it about; it was as nameless as the anxiety you feel in the small hours of the morning. My spanking fantasies reflected that guilt; they were a mild and exciting way to feel it without tying it to something painful. There was some strange shuttlecock effect in my life about feeling bad and feeling good; I was a afraid to let myself feel too good; if I was feeling too good I would use my guilt feelings to make myself feel bad. This dynamic was reflected in the rhythm of my work: I would get down on myself, make myself feel bad, in order to make up for it with the work I did; it was a method for getting work done. Other ways of getting myself down reflected the same general strategy: psychosomatic ailments, hypochondria, endless worry over things I couldn&rsquo;t change. My consciousness was jammed with the these things; they had crowded out everything else. And in all these ways &mdash; like the governess brandishing the cane over the boy&rsquo;s bare buttocks, whose white flesh was already criss-crossed with a network of red stripes (I can still write this stuff; it&rsquo;s like riding a bicycle) &mdash; I was punishing myself.</p>

<p>I thought to myself &mdash; and it was like a vision of paradise, or of perfect health &mdash; what if I allowed myself to live without punishing myself? What would that be like? It was almost unimaginable. It was frightening. What would fill my consciousness, if it were emptied of all those other things?</p>

<p>What would fill it, of course, would be the present moment.</p>

<p>For the second time in my life, many years after the first, I had seen a way in which my sexual fantasies were inextricably linked up with who I was as a person. In this case &mdash; and it is still a recent revelation, which has not necessarily played itself out &mdash; the connection seems more problematic. The strongest feeling I had as I sat in the therapist&rsquo;s office and watched this revelation unfold was that I wanted to stop punishing myself. I wanted to feel pleasure and joy without punishing myself with guilt. That would seem to mean, for instance, making love without acting out or fantasizing scenes of punishment. Not that I want to scorn such fantasies if they arise, as if there were something wrong with them: that in itself would produce guilt. In that moment in the therapist&rsquo;s office, when I saw what was behind those fantasies, it was as if they were a giant inflatable toy that I had just stuck with a pin. They had loomed so large and bright that they seemed real. In a matter of seconds they went utterly flat.</p>

<p>They have disappeared before. I won&rsquo;t be surprised if they return. Fantasies that have been with you for most of a lifetime don&rsquo;t often vanish in a matter of seconds. I do think that, if they return, the place to face them will be in a context of play. There, they can be exciting. They can be held up to the light and seen for what they are. The guilt they reflect, however, is not to be played with. It plays with you.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I love this part on a woman.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Most men do.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;The little hill it forms when you lie on your belly like this.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;The little valley down the middle.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;What does it make you want to do?&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Put my face there?&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Do it.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I&rsquo;d like to kiss.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Isn&rsquo;t that weird?&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Of course not. It&rsquo;s soft and smooth. Lots of men like to kiss there.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I&rsquo;d like to bite.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Gently.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I want to run my tongue .&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;That </em>is<em> dirty.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Not on me.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Does it feel good?&rdquo; </em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s heaven.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I&rsquo;d like to give it a little smack.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Not too hard.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Of course not.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Oh! That was nice. A little smack is nice.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I know.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Ow! That was too hard.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m sorry.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;How dare you treat your French teacher that way!&rdquo; </em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I kind of .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. forgot where I was.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;You won&rsquo;t forget again. Come up here this instant.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t mean it. I just forgot.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Whether you meant it or not. I won&rsquo;t be treated this way. Turn over on this bed.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ll never do it again.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;You certainly won&rsquo;t. Now do as I say.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Sex is thought to be an adult activity. At least adults do it a lot &mdash; often in a very serious, adult way &mdash; and children, when they do sexual things, are often punished for them. But when I think of what sex involves.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. Bare bodies. Big hugs. Smacks. Tickling. Giggling. Caresses. Whispers in the dark. Licking. Sucking. Squishy noises. The mess it makes. It all seems childish to me. It seems innocent.</p>

<p>A major part of sex is physical, and that part is very good. Yet it is never, even in the most casual encounter, just physical. Nothing in life is just physical. It is also psychic. Emotional. Spiritual. It teaches something. (Not the way one person in a classroom says something and another person hears it. The way an experience teaches you something. It becomes a part of you.) It is a psychic playground. You can try whatever you like. The fact that many people &mdash; terribly adult people &mdash; don&rsquo;t notice this aspect of sex doesn&rsquo;t mean it isn&rsquo;t there. Those people fail to notice a lot of things.</p>

<p>I am well aware that my wish to be hugged from head to toe, belly to belly, that warm close embrace that says I love and accept you, that vision of acceptance that has sent me into the arms of numerous women and caused me a great deal of anguish, really expresses my need to love myself. No woman can give me that acceptance. The very fact that I&rsquo;ve gone to so many for it &mdash; repeated the scene so many times &mdash; lets me know that I&rsquo;m seeking something that can&rsquo;t be found there. The wish to lie back and get blown expresses a tendency toward passivity on my part, and also a wish for acceptance of my sexuality &mdash; she likes it so much that she takes it in her mouth! she lets me come! she swallows the come! &mdash; that I need to give myself. <em>I</em> need to love my cock. The wish to be thrown over a woman&rsquo;s knee and spanked expresses a longing to be freed from guilt that only I can free myself from. No woman can do that for me.</p>

<p>It is sex &mdash; what some people would call my obsession with sex &mdash; that has taught me these things.</p>

<p>Knowing them, I still love to be hugged that way. I love to lie back and get blown. I may well enjoy being spanked again.</p>

<p>I was walking down Park Avenue in New York not long ago with a writer friend &mdash; the perfect place to have this conversation &mdash; when he said, &ldquo;Sometimes I think if I get my novel published I&rsquo;ll go on the college lecture circuit and get laid a lot. Do you ever think a thing like that?&rdquo; Absolutely. Most men would understand that fantasy. I&rsquo;ve had similar ones since my earliest youth. After all these years of having such a dream myself, though, I don&rsquo;t think my friend really wants to get laid a lot. That is a metaphor for what he wants. I think he wants to have written a great and wonderful novel, to be loved and admired for it. That is the wish that seems presumptuous. The desire that dares not speak its name. It strips you bare to admit such a thing. So you say you want to get laid.</p>

<p>A woman friend tells me she thinks you bring everything you are feeling to an act of sex, that it all comes out in that moment. It is just as true that you bring your whole life to it. What you do in bed might show you as you are. It might express things that you can&rsquo;t express elsewhere. You might find things there that you want to take out into the rest of your life. A woman raised in the middle of this century, taught always to defer to men, always to please them, might find it hard to express her own needs and stand up for them. In bed, with a man who understands, she might have a chance to do that. A man raised in the middle of this century, taught that he was always supposed to know things, to take the lead, might wish to abrogate that responsibility, to go back to the time when he took up this burden, and hand it back to the woman. Not every time they make love, but sometimes. It&rsquo;s a chance to change the way things have always felt. It&rsquo;s a game a couple can play.</p>

<p>He can even pretend it&rsquo;s his first time in bed, with his French teacher.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Do you think it&rsquo;s big?&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Do you think it&rsquo;s very big?&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;As a matter of fact I do. I think it&rsquo;s enormous. I&rsquo;ve never seen one like it. And you&rsquo;re still just a boy!&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Have you seen a lot?&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Hundreds. Thousands. I haven&rsquo;t kept count. Check my memoirs.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;What do I do now?&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;You put it in me.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;The whole thing?&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Every last inch.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Do I ram it in hard?&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;No. Gently. Slowly. When it gets real hot and wet, you do it hard.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Really?&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;You bang me. You bang my box.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Jesus. What if I do it too hard?&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ll tell you.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Should I do it now?&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Right now.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m not sure where it goes.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ll show you. If I can get my hand around this enormous .&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;All my life I&rsquo;ve wanted to do this.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I know.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ve wanted to find a woman who would show me.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I still can&rsquo;t believe it&rsquo;s happening.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;It is.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;I can&rsquo;t believe that for once I&rsquo;ve been so lucky.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;You&rsquo;re going to believe it now.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Oh!&rsquo;&rsquo;</em></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="text-center"><strong>III</strong></p>

<p>The activity in my life that most reminds me of sex is writing.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="text-center"><strong>IV</strong></p>

<p>Some years ago, around the time I quit my part-time job, I would sometimes be writing in my study and hear my son in the backyard with a friend.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Let&rsquo;s say we&rsquo;ve just gotten out of the Enterprise and we&rsquo;re checking our phasers.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;No! We&rsquo;re in a land rover and we left our phasers back at the ship.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;OK. We&rsquo;re riding along and at first we don&rsquo;t see anything.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The neighborhood would be quiet, people off at work. The boys&rsquo; voices traveled across a mild breeze. I would smile, and think to myself, I&rsquo;m doing the same thing they are.</p>

<p>People sometimes questioned, in those days, the way I brought up my son. &ldquo;You let your son play with guns?&rdquo; they would say, in open-mouthed astonishment. &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t you realize that leads to violent behavior later in life? Someday he&rsquo;ll think if he&rsquo;s having trouble with a friend the answer is just to take a gun out and vaporize him.&rdquo; This statement ignored the fact that I had played with guns as a child, but didn&rsquo;t resort to violence in my adult life (though I was sorely tempted at that very moment). I would try to explain that I thought my son, in his play, was confronting his fears about the world, real dangers and imaginary ones. He was bringing them up in a context he could handle, and dealing with them as best he could. When he was young, and the things he feared seemed large and overwhelming, it was important for him to believe he could vaporize them. Otherwise he couldn&rsquo;t face them, and facing them was important. Later he would learn things weren&rsquo;t so black and white, that you couldn&rsquo;t identify the bad guys so easily or deal with them so simply. The phase he was going through was an important step. He was using play to help him deal with reality.</p>

<p>That&rsquo;s what I was doing too. Using play to help me deal with reality.</p>

<p>Was it important, what we were doing? Was it worth our time? Just playing, people often say. We were just playing. I have often thought that a measure of an activity&rsquo;s value is how it holds one&rsquo;s attention or captures one&rsquo;s energy. It sometimes seems that activities that the world regards as vastly important don&rsquo;t rank very high on that scale (it is said, for example, that our President falls asleep at his Cabinet meetings). I have noticed, in places where I&rsquo;ve worked, that people often leave their place of employment with much more energy and enthusiasm for what they&rsquo;re about to do than for what they&rsquo;ve just done, even if they&rsquo;re only going off to have a beer. &ldquo;What kind of world would this be if people didn&rsquo;t have to work?&rdquo; I have heard people say, angrily. What kind of world would it be if people gave themselves to what they&rsquo;re doing the way children give themselves to play?</p>

<p>Behind all questions about work and play are much larger ones: What should we give our lives to? How should we spend our days? Some years ago, when it looked as if the world of industry might be taken over by automation, people wondered what it would be like if we didn&rsquo;t have jobs. Would the world become a utopia, or would we all go out of our minds? Would people take up valuable hobbies? Leathercraft? Woodworking? Or would they sit in a stupor in front of the tube all day?</p>

<p>The debate seemed to come down to the question of whether the average person would be better off on the Ford assembly line or down at the bowling alley; the consensus seemed to be that he&rsquo;d better stay on the assembly line. No telling what he might do if he got tired of bowling. Perhaps. Assuming the camaraderie were about the same at both places (I&rsquo;m not at all sure that&rsquo;s true), he might be better off on the assembly line, since that would give him at least some feeling of accomplishment. It seems a shame to be settling for such minimal satisfactions.</p>

<p>Where this debate got off the track was when it grouped all kinds of leisure activities together. You could read or you could play golf. Play an instrument or play croquet. Tennis, bowling, bingo, square dancing are important amusements of a kind that people should have in their lives, especially when they bring friends together, but they are not what I am speaking of here as play. When I think of play I think of the intensity my son had at the age of six when he played Star Trek, of the apparently effortless intensity he has now when he is working on the comic books he produces (a kind of intensity I seldom see in adults). I think of play as a higher activity than work, something that engages a person the way art does, or literature, or music. Intense conversation. A beautiful evening sky. Great sex. I mean the kind of play that could be at the center of your life, the kind of thing you might say you live for. I don&rsquo;t know what kind of world this would be if people didn&rsquo;t have to work. I think it would be a much better world if they could learn really to give themselves to play.</p>
														</div>


				
